---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Breadcrumbs from '../../../components/Breadcrumbs.astro';
import FAQ from '../../../components/FAQ.astro';
import { articleSchema, breadcrumbSchema, faqSchema, productReviewSchema } from '../../../lib/schema';

const title = 'Honda HRX 476 VK Review — The 20-Year Mower (2026)';
const description = "Honda HRX 476 VK petrol mower long-term review. GXV160 engine, Xenoy deck, Versamow mulching — tested over 4 years on a large UK lawn. The ultimate domestic mower.";
const path = '/reviews/honda-hrx-476-vk/';
const datePublished = '2026-05-10';

const crumbs = [
  { name: 'Home', url: '/' },
  { name: 'Petrol lawn mowers', url: '/petrol-lawn-mowers/' },
  { name: 'Honda HRX 476 VK review', url: path },
];

const faqs = [
  { q: 'Is the Honda HRX 476 worth £999?', a: 'If you plan to keep it for 15–20 years (and many owners do), the cost-per-year is under £50. The GXV160 engine, Xenoy deck, and Honda build quality mean this mower will still be cutting lawns when cheaper rivals are in a skip. For lifetime value, it\'s actually rational — just painful upfront.' },
  { q: 'What is a Xenoy deck?', a: 'Xenoy is a high-impact polymer that Honda uses instead of steel or aluminium. It won\'t rust, won\'t dent, is lighter than steel, and handles impacts that would crack standard plastic. It\'s one of the main reasons Honda mowers last so long.' },
  { q: 'What does Versamow do?', a: 'Versamow is Honda\'s variable mulching system — a sliding lever that lets you choose anywhere between 100% collection and 100% mulching, or any ratio in between. You can mulch most clippings while collecting just the excess. Genuinely useful and unique to Honda.' },
  { q: 'Honda HRX 476 vs Mountfield SP46 — is Honda worth 3x the price?', a: 'In pure mowing terms, no — the Mountfield cuts grass adequately for £329. The Honda premium buys you: engine longevity (20+ years vs 8–10), Xenoy deck (never rusts), Versamow mulching system, 5-year warranty, and higher resale value. If you keep mowers for 5 years, Mountfield wins on value. If you keep them for 15+, Honda wins.' },
  { q: 'How long does a Honda HRX last?', a: 'With annual servicing (oil, plug, filter — about £30 in parts), 20+ years of domestic use is entirely normal. The GXV160 engine is the same unit Honda puts in commercial pressure washers. Parts availability is guaranteed for decades.' },
];

const schema = [
  breadcrumbSchema(crumbs),
  articleSchema({ headline: title, description, url: path, datePublished, dateModified: datePublished }),
  faqSchema(faqs),
  productReviewSchema({ name: 'Honda HRX 476 VK', brand: 'Honda', description, rating: 4.8, url: path, datePublished, reviewBody: 'The domestic mower that lasts 20 years. GXV160 engine, Xenoy deck, Versamow mulching. Expensive once — cheap forever. The best petrol mower money can buy for UK lawns.' }),
];
---
<BaseLayout {title} {description} {schema}>
  <article class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 py-10">
    <Breadcrumbs items={crumbs} />

    <header class="mb-8">
      <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-grass-700 uppercase tracking-wide mb-2">Long-term review · Updated May 2026</p>
      <h1 class="text-3xl md:text-5xl font-bold text-soil-900 leading-tight">Honda HRX 476 VK Review</h1>
      <p class="mt-3 text-slate-500 text-sm">By The Best Mowers UK · 4 years on a 900 m² Wiltshire lawn</p>
    </header>

    <aside class="bg-grass-50 border-l-4 border-grass-700 rounded-r-lg p-5 mb-10">
      <div class="flex items-start justify-between gap-4 mb-3">
        <div>
          <p class="text-xs font-bold text-grass-700 uppercase tracking-wide mb-1">Our verdict</p>
          <p class="text-2xl font-bold text-soil-900">4.8 / 5</p>
        </div>
        <div class="text-right text-sm">
          <p class="font-semibold text-soil-900">£999 RRP</p>
          <p class="text-slate-500">Best petrol mower overall</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
        Four years in, our Honda HRX 476 VK starts on the first pull, cuts as cleanly as the day we unboxed it, and shows zero signs of age. The GXV160 engine is bulletproof. The Xenoy deck will never rust. The Versamow system means you rarely need to empty the box. It\'s £999 — but divide that by the 20 years it\'ll last and it\'s £50 a year for the best domestic mower available in the UK. Nothing else comes close on lifetime value.
      </p>
    </aside>

    <div class="prose-mowers">
      <h2>Specs</h2>
      <table>
        <tbody>
          <tr><th>Cutting width</th><td>47 cm</td></tr>
          <tr><th>Engine</th><td>Honda GXV160 (163 cc OHV)</td></tr>
          <tr><th>Deck</th><td>Xenoy (high-impact polymer)</td></tr>
          <tr><th>Drive</th><td>Variable-speed self-propelled</td></tr>
          <tr><th>Cut heights</th><td>7 positions, 20–80 mm</td></tr>
          <tr><th>Grass box</th><td>73 litres</td></tr>
          <tr><th>Mulching</th><td>Yes — Versamow (variable ratio)</td></tr>
          <tr><th>Side discharge</th><td>Yes</td></tr>
          <tr><th>Weight</th><td>36 kg</td></tr>
          <tr><th>Warranty</th><td>5 years (domestic)</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h2>What we loved</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>GXV160 engine reliability</strong> — first-pull start every single time across 4 years. No choke fiddling, no stalling, no servicing issues. Honda engineering at its finest.</li>
        <li><strong>Versamow mulching</strong> — slide the lever to choose your collect/mulch ratio. In dry summer we mulch 80% and collect the excess. Saves emptying the box every 5 minutes.</li>
        <li><strong>Xenoy deck</strong> — no rust, ever. Lighter than steel, tougher than standard plastic. After 4 years of being bashed into edging stones it shows no damage.</li>
        <li><strong>73L grass box</strong> — enormous. On our 900 m² test lawn, one empty per mow when mulching at 50%.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>What we didn\'t love</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>£999 upfront</strong> — the elephant in the room. Most people baulk at spending this much on a mower. Understandable, even if the lifetime economics are sound.</li>
        <li><strong>36 kg</strong> — it\'s a substantial machine. Variable-speed drive makes it effortless on flat ground, but lifting it into a raised shed requires two hands and some determination.</li>
        <li><strong>No rear roller</strong> — for a mower this expensive, the lack of defined stripes is disappointing. You get directional marks but not Hayter-level lines.</li>
        <li><strong>Overkill for small lawns</strong> — under 400 m², you\'re wasting the 47 cm deck capacity. A Bosch cordless would serve you better and cheaper.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>How it compares</h2>
      <p>
        The <a href="/reviews/mountfield-sp46/">Mountfield SP46</a> at £329 delivers 80% of the performance at 33% of the price — the rational budget choice. The <a href="/reviews/hayter-harrier-41/">Hayter Harrier 41</a> at £899 is the alternative if stripes matter more than versatility — rear roller, better lines, no mulching. The <a href="/reviews/ego-lm2122e-sp/">EGO LM2122E-SP</a> at £549 is the cordless alternative that matches Honda\'s cutting performance without fuel or servicing.
      </p>

      <h2>Who should buy it</h2>
      <p>
        Owners of large UK lawns (600–1,500 m²) who want a mower they\'ll keep for 15–20 years. Buyers who hate replacing things — who\'d rather pay more once than buy cheaper three times. Anyone who values Japanese engineering, Versamow mulching flexibility, and the peace of mind that comes with Honda reliability.
      </p>
      <p>
        Don\'t buy it if your lawn is under 400 m² (overkill — go cordless), if stripes are your priority (Hayter Harrier with a rear roller), or if you\'re switching to cordless anyway (EGO LM2122E-SP at half the price).
      </p>
    </div>

    <FAQ {faqs} />
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
